se that model, they'd align with the workspace configuration and shouldn't trigger a switch error. But there's a fundamental contradiction here—the workspace rule says to use minimax for simple tasks, yet the cron jobs keep getting killed by a model switch error that requests minimax instead. Let me reconsider what's actually happening with the switch request.\n\nLooking at the cron task configuration more carefully, the model is explicitly set to minimax, so why would it trigger a switch to minimax? Maybe the gpt-5.4 model itself is actually unavailable or failing, and the real issue is that I switched the cron jobs away from minimax when they were originally configured for it. The user's complaint that gpt-5.4 isn't working anymore suggests I broke something by changing the model assignment. I see the issue now - the cron jobs are actually using minimax-m2.7, which is conflicting with the workspace configuration that expects minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7. The old error message was confusing because it was triggering a switch to the portal version when the cron was already trying to use the local version. Let me just switch everything back to minimax as the user requested and see if that resolves the connectivity issues. I see the real issue now - the cron task is using `main` as the agentId, which resolves to gpt-5.4 by default, but the workspace USER.md is trying to enforce minimax-m2.7 as the model. So the fix would be to either set the cron task's model to minimax-m2.7 explicitly, or change the USER.md default - and the user is saying gpt-5.4 isn't working, so I should probably go with updating the workspace configuration to match what the cron is actually trying to use. I see the real issue now - if I set the cron job to minimax, it would try to switch to minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7 due to the workspace configuration, which is exactly what caused the LiveSessionModelSwitchError before. The workspace itself is triggering this error when it overrides the model's default behavior. This is a fundamental conflict - I need to figure out whether to change the workspace USER.md to accept minimax-m2.7 as a valid model, or find another approach entirely. I think the real issue is that `minimax-m2.7` isn't a valid model identifier in the config—it's being treated as an unknown model and then switching to `minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7`. The solution is to either use the full `minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7` model name in the cron job, or reconfigure the USER.md default to use `minimax-m2.7` instead of the portal variant. I'm realizing the USER.md model specification might not actually override the agent's system-level configuration when explicit models are set, so the cron jobs were likely defaulting to gpt-5.4 anyway. Let me just try switching back to minimax as the user requested and see if the error recurs—if it does, we can dig deeper into the actual model routing. I'll update all the cron job models to use `minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7` instead of `minimax-m2.7`, since that should be the consistent model identifier across both the workspace and cron configurations.","thinkingSignature":"67bf1e3eebdd78c0e414751b3061c8b46add9fad386922ac6c569d21d04b2c44"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_z7h4attnpcbu_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/cron/jobs.json | python3 -c \"\nimport json, sys\ndata = json.load(sys.stdin)\n\ntarget_ids = {\n    'investment-research-data-source-health-0935',\n    'investment-research-event-watch-0945',\n    'investment-research-background-intraday-1030',\n    'investment-research-background-postclose-1630',\n    'investment-research-background-overnight-2100',\n}\n\nfixed = []\nfor job in data.get('jobs', []):\n    if job.get('id') in target_ids:\n        old = job.get('payload', {}).get('model', '')\n        # Use the full model string that matches workspace default\n        job['payload']['model'] = 'minimax-portal/MiniMax-M2.7'\n        job['state']['consecutiveErrors'] = 0\n        jo